name: Dave Young
tweet: Happy #WomensHistoryMonth! Today I’d like to highlight Ellis Meredith who was known as the Susan B. Anthony of Colorado. Meredith was a political journalist who would go on to lead the suffragist movement in Colorado.

name: Dave Young
tweet: Happy International Women’s Day! Women have made great strides in the state of Colorado, including in our own state legislature. Did you know that women make up the majority of Democratic Representatives & Senators? That includes my own wife, Rep. Mary Young, who represents HD50!

name: Dave Young
tweet: Happy #WomensHistoryMonth! Today I’d like to highlight Molly Brown. Brown famously survived the sinking of the Titanic, but she was also a suffragist and helped create the Colorado Chapter of the National American Women’s Suffrage Association.

name: Dave Young
tweet: Today for #BlackHistoryMonth, I’d like to highlight Madame CJ Walker. Walker was the first woman self-made millionaire. She gained her fortune by developing and selling hair care products to Black women!

name: Dave Young
tweet: Happy #BlackHistoryMonth! Today, I’d like to highlight Ada B. Evans, Colorado’s first black mayor. She was elected mayor of Fairplay in 1974 and served for two terms as mayor. Later, she continued to serve her community as a social service case manager.

name: Dave Young
tweet: Happy #BlackHistoryMonth! OT Jackson was a businessman who established Dearfield, Colorado, a homesteading settlement for African Americans in Weld County. Today, two UNC professors Bob Brunswig and George Junne are leading the charge to study and restore Dearfield!

name: Dave Young
tweet: Happy #BlackHistoryMonth! Today I'd like to highlight Jim Beckwourth who was one of the earliest fur trappers of the Rockies and a co-founder of the city of Pueblo. You can find a complete account of his adventures in his autobiography:  https://t.co/vVTp5yY6vj

name: Dave Young
tweet: Today, I’d like to highlight Dr. Justina Ford, Denver’s very first female Black doctor. Because she wasn’t able to work in hospitals, she began practicing out of her own home. By the time her career ended, it’s estimated that she delivered almost 7,000 babies! #BlackHistoryMonth

name: Dave Young
tweet: In honor of #BlackHistoryMonth, I want to share some stories of Black Coloradans. George Leslie Brown was our nation’s first Black Lt. Gov. In 1955, he was elected as a State Rep. and was later elected to the State Senate where he was re-elected 5 times and served for 18 years!

name: Dave Young
tweet: 13 years ago, President Obama signed the Lilly Ledbetter Fair Pay Act, requiring employers to ensure nondiscriminatory pay practices. We must continue to strengthen existing protections & enact policies that will help alleviate disadvantages women face in the workplace.

name: Dave Young
tweet: 49 years ago, Shirley Chisholm began her historic run for president. She was a champion of racial and gender equity and paved the way for so many who came after her. Of her legacy, Chisholm said, “I want to be remembered as a woman…who dared to be a catalyst of change.”

name: Dave Young
tweet: 49 years ago, the Supreme Court ruled that women have the right to make a decision about their reproductive care without excessive government restriction. Today, those hard-earned rights are under attack. We must all do our part to protect reproductive autonomy!

name: Dave Young
tweet: For 17 years, the “Don’t Ask, Don’t Tell” ban on LGBTQ+ servicemembers sent a message that discrimination was acceptable. 11 years ago, that harmful practice ended. There’s still work to do to ensure that all members of the LGBTQ+ community are treated equally under the law.

name: Dave Young
tweet: 77 years ago today, a declaration ended Japanese internment in the United States. This shameful past cannot be forgotten, which is why @MichaelBennet is working to make Colorado’s Camp Amache part of our national park system.

name: Dave Young
tweet: It’s been 9 years since the fateful day at Sandy Hook Elementary School that ended the lives of over two dozen people. Colorado is no stranger to the epidemic of gun violence, & it’s critical that we put in the work to prevent tragedies like this from happening in the future.

name: Dave Young
tweet: Today is #HumanRightsDay, which celebrates the day in 1948 when the United Nations adopted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. We still have work to do across the globe to ensure these inalienable rights are honored, & this document is an important precedent to that work.

name: Dave Young
tweet: 80 years ago, thousands of Americans lost their lives while serving their country in Pearl Harbor. My father enlisted after the attack on Pearl Harbor and worked in military intelligence. It's thanks to his bravery & the bravery of our troops today that we enjoy our freedoms.

name: Dave Young
tweet: 66 years ago, Rosa Parks refused to give up her seat on a bus, and her refusal led to her arrest and subsequently the Montgomery bus boycott. Her bravery made her an icon in the Civil Rights movement, and her legacy will not be forgotten.
